whereas almost everyone could clearly articulate the things they were less good at or wanted

51
00:03:48,590 --> 00:03:50,260
to develop.

52
00:03:50,260 --> 00:03:53,580
Interestingly, research shows the importance of strengths

53
00:03:53,580 --> 00:03:55,560
above anything else.

54
00:03:55,560 --> 00:03:58,510
Let me give you a couple of examples.

55
00:03:58,510 --> 00:04:02,880
Researchers looked for the strongest predictor for high performance teams.

56
00:04:02,880 --> 00:04:05,060
The answer?

57
00:04:05,060 --> 00:04:10,680
The number of team members that indicated they are using their strengths every day.

58
00:04:10,680 --> 00:04:16,289
Another research study quotes the observation of bowling teams in 1982.

59
00:04:16,289 --> 00:04:19,160
They focused on two teams.

60
00:04:19,160 --> 00:04:24,029
Team 1 was shown a video highlighting only mistakes in previous games.

61
00:04:24,029 --> 00:04:28,520
Team 2 was shown a video highlighting only successes.

62
00:04:28,520 --> 00:04:31,740
In fact, both teams got better.

63
00:04:31,740 --> 00:04:38,360
But the team that saw the video with the successes, improved twice as much as the other team!

64
00:04:38,360 --> 00:04:42,360
Furthermore, this research shows that people grow the most

65
00:04:42,360 --> 00:04:46,919
in areas in which people already show high performance to begin with.

66
00:04:46,919 --> 00:04:49,210
When we are children, we find this very logical.

67
00:04:49,210 --> 00:04:53,999
Anna is good at math, so she finds it easy to learn the new mathematics

68
00:04:53,999 --> 00:04:54,439
material.

69
00:04:54,439 --> 00:04:58,080
Timmy is good at English, and he also learns the new English material

70
00:04:58,080 --> 00:05:01,900
more easily than new material in other courses.

71
00:05:01,900 --> 00:05:05,699
